  "prompt": "What are the symptoms of a heart cancer?",
  "response": "Heart cancer, also known as primary cardiac cancer, is extremely rare. The heart is an unusual location for tumors to develop, and most cancers found in the heart are metastatic, meaning they have spread from other parts of the body. However, when primary heart cancers do occur, they are typically malignant (cancerous) and can present with a variety of symptoms depending on their size, location, and how they affect the heart's normal function. Common symptoms may include:\n\n1. **Shortness of Breath:** Difficulty breathing can occur if the tumor interferes with the heart's ability to pump blood effectively.\n\n2. **Chest Pain or Discomfort:** Pain may arise from the tumor pressing against heart tissues or surrounding structures.\n\n3. **Irregular Heartbeats (Arrhythmias):** Tumors can disrupt the electrical pathways of the heart, leading to palpitations or an irregular heartbeat.\n\n4. **Fatigue:** Reduced heart function can lead to a general feeling of tiredness or weakness.\n\n5. **Swelling in the Legs or Abdomen:** If the heart's pumping efficiency is compromised, fluid may accumulate in the lower extremities or abdominal area.\n\n6. **Cough or Coughing Up Blood:** Pressure from a tumor on airways can cause persistent coughing or even hemoptysis (coughing up blood).\n\n7. **Fainting or Dizziness:** Reduced blood flow to the brain can result in lightheadedness or fainting episodes.\n\n8. **Weight Loss and Loss of Appetite:** Unintended weight loss and decreased appetite may occur as the body's metabolism is affected.\n\nIt's important to note that these symptoms are not specific to heart cancer and can be associated with a wide range of other cardiovascular and non-cardiovascular conditions. If you or someone you know is experiencing these symptoms, it's crucial to seek medical attention promptly for accurate diagnosis and appropriate management.\n\n**Disclaimer:** This information is intended for educational purposes only and does not substitute professional medical advice. If you have concerns about your health, please consult a healthcare professional.",
